  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT257-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">varaivuṇarttiya tōḻikkuk kiḻatti uraittatu. </p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Told by HER to the confidante who announced marriage. </p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT257">
        <lg type="edition">
          <l>vēru mutaluṅ kōṭu morāṅkut</l>
          <l>toṭutta pōlat tūṅkupu toṭarik</l>
          <l>kīḻtāḻ vaṉṉa vīḻkōṭ palavi</l>
          <l>ṉārkali veṟpaṉ varutoṟum varūu</l>
          <l>makaliṉu makalā tāki</l>
          <l>yikalun tōḻinaṅ kāmattup pakaiyē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l>Ever when the man from the bustling <note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">ār kali</term>
            : here the formulaic epithet is problematic (cf. note on KT 155.1). How can a mountain
            be noisy? Bustling with life, in a figurative sense, might be conceivable. Or is it the <term
                xml:lang="ta">veṟpaṉ</term> himself who is very busy?</note> mountain comes,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">with jack trees with descending bundles <note place="foot">What does <term
                xml:lang="ta">kōḷ</term> here refer to? Bundles of fruit? But what, then, is the
            nuance of <term xml:lang="ta">vīḻ</term> ? The weight of the many fruit hanging so low?
            T.V.G. explains it as "bundles of fruit desired by all".</note>
          </l>
          <l rend="indent8">as if hanging down to the ground <note place="foot">Is this the meaning
            of <term xml:lang="ta">kīḻ tāḻ</term> here? T.V.G. thinks the fruit seem almost to fall
            down to the ground.</note> ,</l>
          <l rend="indent4">hanging [and] linked [to each other] as if</l>
          <l rend="indent4">root and base and branch were linked into one, <note place="foot">Syntax
            and message of the first three lines are far from clear. Some kind of word-play,
            however, is implied: there is a triad of words of comparison (<term xml:lang="ta">āṅku –
            pōla – aṉṉa</term>) and of verbs for a descending movement (<term xml:lang="ta">tūṅkupu
            – kīḻ tāḻ – vīḻ</term> ).</note>
          </l>
          <l>comes our enemy [in the form] of desire <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta">kāmattu</term> : the oblique can be
            understood here as a genitivus explicativus.</note> , friend, which is hostile,</l>
          <l>being one not to depart, when [he] departs.</l>


        </lg>
      </div>
